Trollveggen (Troll Wall) is the tallest vertical rock face in Europe. It's popular with climbers and base jumpers alike. While searching for accurate, real-world terrain models, I found the site "Terrafab". This amazing website lets you draw a box around any piece of land in Norway and generate a 3D terrain model for that area. You can either get that model printed in full color or --and this is the amazing part-- you can just download the model for free! Guys at Terrafab, if you're reading this, THANK YOU! It's a wonderful service and there are some really neat geological features to explore in Norway (like Trollveggen and Galdhopiggen). So folks, if you have a chance, check out: http://terrafab.bengler.no/ If anyone knows of a similar service that covers other parts of the world, or any good way of generating 3D terrain models of real places, please share in the comments section. comments.text:
Bonjour et ...merci,
Oui ça a été difficile de dessiner cet engrenage. j'ai beaucoup utilisé le modèle original de la montre pour repérer les formes de denture.
Ensuite, j'ai compté le nombre de dents par côté du carré, ici 15.
J'ai ensuite tracé la base de la denture, en conservant le même pas, ici le côté du carré divisé par 15.
en traçant des lignes du centre du carré vers la pointe des dents, j'avais le direction, ensuite, construction des dents classiques.
Idem pour l'engrenage rond, la longueur de chaque "portion de cercle" devait être égal à la longueur du carré.
pourquoi 15 dents?, je suppose que le fabricant de montre à voulu que un tour de l'engrenage carré fasse 1 minute (4x15 s)
60 dents en tout.
Ensuite j'ai utilisé mon logiciel topsolid7 pour vérifier le bonne connexion entre chaque dent. Il a fallu faire quelque corrections.
Je suivais la forme originale également.
j'ai utilisé des arcs de cercle plutôt que des développantes de cercle, vu la différence à petite échelle, ce n'est pas la peine.
Et ça fonctionne bien. Le système n'est pas prévu pour tourner des millions de fois comme sur une montre!
Voilà, c'est un peu empirique, mais on y arrive. Tout faire par le calcul, c'était trop de temps. Je vais mettre une photo pour vous montrer aussi que un détail qui parait gros sur le dessin, ne se voit pas sur l'impression.
Bonne journée,
NOP21

description.text:
As a relatively new owner of a RV Camp Trailer, I was dismayed to find that the Norcold refrigerator had problems cooling. After talking with other RV owners, the dealership, and their technical lead who serviced the refrigerator, it was determined that passive refrigerators (ones that do not have a circulation fan) are infamous for taking a couple of days to reach normal operating temperature. This information was confirmed by many camper forums of people with similar issues being able to resolve it by purchasing a recirculation fan.

Searching on Amazon showed several recirculation fans but they cost upward of $20 and I knew I could do better. This design is the initial release of my first attempt. It uses a standard 80mm computer case fan sandwiched between two shells and a 12V battery pack (see pictures). In-the-field testing will occur shortly to see if this design actually works from a cooling perspective as all technical research indicates a successful design.

Note: The roughness of the internal open areas on the shells is due to the fact that my slicer decided to add a 3 bead wide brim and it had to be manually removed with a razor knife. Also, I assembled this without coffee and my hands aren't all that steady.

Printer:

Monoprice MP Select Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

It is recommended to use scaffolding on this print to ensure that the screwhole plates are not deformed. Infill can be set to any percentage however at least 20% is recommended. The prints above used a 40% infill.

Parts required
  • 1x 12V (8x AA) power pack with 9V-snap style connector.
  • 1x 9V snap connector
  • 1x 80mm 12V computer case fan (clear recommended so you can see if the fan is spinning). LED lit fans not recommended because of battery longevity reasons.
  • 8x case fan screws.
Assembly

Assembly is straight forward, the only suggestion I have is to make sure the recirculation fan points down (blows towards the bottom shell).

Wiring - Red to red, black to black, ignore yellow wire.

One very useful fixture I used long time ago when for pad printing process. Extremely useful where fast lock/unlock is required in combination with big external forces.

If unlocked it allows free XY movement and free rotation in quite big range (in this case 50-60mm). When locked it becomes rock solid, there is no problem to do even milling on the detail attached to the fixture - it can withstand large forces.

By simply screwing and unscrewing a screw the fixture could be locked or unlocked - very fast operation in slim design. A short animation is available on:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ti3kszMwe2I

SolidWorks design files and IGES were added.

The secret how it works is in the compressing ring - it has slant edge which stays against the sharp edge of the screw. When screwing the screw the edge is pushing the slant edge and creates substantial force down which is transferred to the top plate. The end result is - top plate is pressed against the bottom plate and the friction creates extremely strong and robust lock.

The initial design was made from aluminum but there is no problem to 3D print some parts. I would recommend the compressing ring to be made from metal (steel) on lathe.

Adding some tacky oil between top and bottom plate makes the movements (when unlocked) very smooth, you can position precisely the details and once you're satisfied with their position you can log the fixture.

Unfortunately the working prototype was lost long time ago but the design remains and I'm pleased to share it now.

description.text:
LED strip desklamp

Please note that I will add another base with cable feed through and one where you can add a button. In addition there will be another modular lamp piece.

This modular lamp was designed for a simple 12V warm white LED strip, but any other kind that is not wider than 1cm should do it. It uses M3 nuts and bolts to connect the pieces. For now you can choose between 2 types of lamp pieces, 2 types of arms and 2 types of bases.

One lamp piece (light_button.stl) has a hole for a little latching button, the other (light.stl) doesn't. The first arm piece (arm_hollow5x4mm_hole.stl) is hollow inside and the other (arm_solid_recess.stl) only has a recess to glue the cable in place. The base (base_hollow_12x140mm.stl) is 12mm thick, 140mm in diameter and is hollow inside, the second one (base_solid_8x140mm.stl) is only 8mm thick, also 140mm in diameter and is solid.

Needed parts
  • 20cm of LED strip
  • a matching power supply
  • at least 2 M3x18 or M3x20(I used these) screws and nuts (metal or plastic should work)
  • cables if needed
  • optionally a latching push button
Assembly in general

Print the parts.
After printing, glue in the 20cm piece of LED strip into the lamp part, by using its adhesive back. Then solder depending on the lamp piece either the cables directly to the terminals of the strip or one wire of your power cable to one terminal of the strip and the other to the button. Pay attention to connect the right cable to the right terminal (+ to + and - to -). Then cut a short cable to go between the button and the strip and solder it in place. Glue the button in place. Now either run down the cable inside the recess and glue it in or feed the wires through the hollow part of the arms. If you chose the hollow base you can put some weight in it through the access hole on the bottom. Enjoy your lamp :)

description.text: This is my NES case for a Raspberry Pi Zero. I have been working on refining the design of this for some time now! Hope you like it!

Printer Brand:

Robo 3D

Printer:

R1 ABS + PLA Model

Rafts:

No

No

Notes:

The top has a rather large bridge to cover where the lid goes, so you might need to use supports (Mine printed without much of an issue)

I printed mine at 1 micron resolution with 33% infill, but I don't think it matters...

What you will need:

4x - #2X1/4" wood screws to secure the Raspberry Pi Zero to the bottom half of the case.

4x - #4X1/2 wood screws to attach the bottom of the case to the top.

A couple small lengths of 1.75mm filament for the hinges on the lid

For the Original version with the switch:

A computer power switch (I salvaged mine from an old computer, but you can also get them online like This one on Amazon

Some super glue to secure the switch and glue filament to lid.

Instructions:

First attach the lid to the top half of the case by sliding a piece of filament through the hinges on the lid and top of case.

Use a small amount of super glue to attach the filament to the lid only (be very careful not to glue the hinges together... I recommend just placing some glue at the very end of the piece of filament in the middle of the lid.

If you use the reset button, there are several tutorials on the webs on how to attach a reset button to your raspberry pi. You need to either solder pins to the "run" section of the board, or just solder the reset button's wires directly to the board. (I soldered pins to my board so I could easily remove the switch if necessary..)

The reset switch will sit in a pocket in the bottom of the case and the reset switch latch should have a small bit of super glue on either side of the latch and placed on the top of the switch to secure it into place.
The button should have the right tolerance to be pressed onto the switch and stay on without glue.

The board should be screwed down to the bottom side of the print with the #2 screws, and the two halves should be screwed together using the #4 screws.

This Instructable will be for making spring PCB holder.

You will need

23mm wide and 64mm high with 2.5mm thick wire. I got my from spare part store for agricultural machines. The one specific is used as valve spring for tractor motor.

6mm thick aluminum rod

http://www.banggood.com/4pcs-N52-205mm-Counterbore-Hole-5mm-Neodymium-Super-Strong-Magnets-p-941810.html

You know how Mac AC power cord has a mind of its own and always want to spring back to a straight line? Yeah, that's cool and everything until you try to coil it up neatly around the Mac AC adaptor and stuff it in your laptop bag. Upon checking it later, you always found that it has managed to turn itself into a rat nest. Well, here comes the rescue. This is a larger and improved version of my earlier "Smartphone USB cable clip (3mm)" design which you can check it out at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:49127.

I used Makerware with 3 shells and 50% infill to print on my Makerbot Replicator. It takes about 15 minutes using ABS. Rafting is not necessary but I always have warping issues on my Replicator so I turned on rafting to help mitigate it.  
It is best to use two of them...
